.SHORT TERM...
Issued at 158 AM PDT Mon Jul 20 2026
(Today and tonight)

A 581 decameter geopotential height low remains located 500 miles
west of San Francisco. The southern branch of the polar/subtropical
jet stream is just forward of this low with jet stream winds to our
southwest through northeast. These jet stream winds have helped
quickly transport high and mid level clouds away from TS Elida in
the last 24 hours or so. GOES-West Geostationary Lightning Mapper
showed lightning approx 600 miles southwest of Point Conception
earlier Sunday, but since Sunday evening it`s been quiet. This
lightning activity was closer to the northward moving and weakening
center of TS Elida.

KMUX has occasionally shown widely scattered high based showers
over our forecast area, but there have been no measurable rain or
lightning reports so far. A band of light high based rain is
developing over the coastal waters as well. We`re in a little bit
of unknown territory here with mainly minor energy transformations
taking place, complexities that occur whenever tropical moisture
travels northward and interacts with the mid-high latitude synoptic
pattern. At the moment, the high based showers/band of light rain
correspond to an area of weaker 500 mb positive vorticity that is
forecast to continue moving northward of our forecast area along
with the aforementioned upper level jet stream. So in a way, the
combination of parameters and the steady diffusing of mid and high
level clouds (water vapor) with minimal to no organization so far
appear to be self limiting, leaning the pattern toward stability,
keeping convective potential at a minimum.

Cloud cover will be a mix of stratus and mid and high level clouds
today. The sun may break out over the southern interior today,
possibly some sunny breaks farther north to the South Bay as well.
Daytime highs today will be about the same it was on Sunday, varying
from the mid to upper 60s along the coast to the 70s bayside to the
80s and 90s well inland. Tonight lows will cool to the 50s except in
the 60s in the hills and mountains.

